{{EngvarB|date=July 2014}} {{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}} {{Infobox Airliner accident |name=Kano air disaster |image=Boeing 707-3D3C JY-ADO Alia LHR 22.08.71 edited-2.jpg |caption=JY-ADO, the aircraft involved in the accident, at [[London Heathrow Airport]] in 1971 |Date= 22 January 1973 |Type= Landing gear collapse, bad weather |occurrence_type = Accident |Site=[[Kano International Airport]] (KAN), Nigeria |Coordinates={{Coord|12|02|58|N|8|31|15|E|display=inline,title}} |Fatalities=176 |Injuries=26 |Aircraft Type=[[Boeing 707]]-3D3C |Operator=[[Royal Jordanian|Alia]] on behalf of [[Nigeria Airways]] |Tail Number= JY-ADO |Origin = [[King Abdulaziz International Airport|King Abdulaziz Int'l Airport, Jeddah]] |Destination =[[Murtala Muhammad International Airport|Ikeja Int'l Airport, Lagos {{small|(now Murtala Muhammad Int'l Airport)}}]] |Passengers=193 |Crew=9 |Survivors=26 }}
The '''Kano air disaster''' was a chartered [[Boeing 707]] passenger flight on 22 January 1973 which crashed while attempting to land at [[Mallam Aminu Kano International Airport|Kano International Airport]]. It is the worst aviation disaster ever to take place in [[Nigeria]],<ref name="ASN">{{ASN accident|id= 19730122-0|title= JY-ADO}}</ref> as 176 passengers and crew perished in the crash. There were 26 survivors.
== Aircraft == The aircraft involved in the accident was a 2 year old [[Boeing 707]]-3D3C, JY-ADO, owned by Alia [[Royal Jordanian|Royal Jordanian Airlines]], operating on behalf of Nigeria Airways. It first flew in 1971 and was powered by 4 [[Pratt & Whitney|Pratt and Whitney]] [[Pratt & Whitney JT3D|JT3D]] engines. It had a [[Serial code|manufacturer serial number]] (MSN) of 850.<ref name="ASN" />
==Flight== The Boeing 707, operated by [[Royal Jordanian|Alia]], had been chartered by [[Nigeria Airways]] to fly [[Hajj|pilgrims]] back from [[Jeddah, Saudi Arabia]] to [[Lagos, Nigeria]]. Bad weather at Lagos caused the crew to divert to [[Kano, Nigeria|Kano]]. [[Mallam Aminu Kano International Airport|Kano International Airport]] was experiencing high winds at the time. The aircraft landed nose wheel first, and the nose wheel collapsed after hitting a depression in the runway.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Accident details|url = http://www.planecrashinfo.com/1973/1973-4.htm|website = www.planecrashinfo.com|access-date = 2016-02-14}}</ref> The right main [[landing gear]] leg subsequently collapsed. The 707 turned 180 degrees, [[Runway excursion|excursed from the runway]] and caught fire.
Of the 202 passengers and crew on board, 176 died and only 26 survived. At the time it occurred, the Kano air disaster was the deadliest-ever aviation accident,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=HKsvAAAAIBAJ&sjid=REwDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5204,1605506&dq=nigeria+airways+kano+crash&hl=en|title=Ludington Daily News - Google News Archive Search|website=news.google.com|access-date=2017-08-29}}</ref> a dubious distinction it only held for about 14 months when [[Turkish Airlines Flight 981]] crashed in France killing 346 people.<ref>{{ASN accident|id= 19740303-1|title= TC-JAV|accessdate= 31 July 2013}}</ref>
