'''Silas Kpanan'Ayoung Siakor''' is a [[Liberia]]n [[environmentalist]].<ref name=grist>{{cite magazine|title=Silas Siakor put his life on the line to save Liberia's forests |url=https://grist.org/article/nijhuis-siakor/ |magazine=[[Grist (magazine) |Grist]]|first=Michelle |last=Nijhuis |authorlink=Michelle Nijhuis |date=25 April 2006 |access-date=6 May 2018 }}</ref><ref name=time>{{cite magazine|title=Silas Kpanan'Ayoung Siakor |url=http://content.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,1841778_1841781_1841809,00.html |magazine=[[Time (magazine) |Time ]]|first=Alex |last=Perry |date=24 September 2008 |access-date=6 May 2018 }}</ref> He was awarded the [[Goldman Environmental Prize]] in 2006, for his revealing of [[illegal logging]] in Liberia and its connection to [[Second Liberian Civil War|the civil war]], leading to export sanctions from the [[United Nations Security Council]].<ref name=goldman>{{cite web |url=https://www.goldmanprize.org/recipient/silas-siakor/ |title=Silas Siakor. 2006 Goldman Prize Recipient Africa |website =goldmanprize.org |access-date=6 May 2018}}</ref>

Silas Siakor was featured in the 2017 film ''Silas'', directed by [[Anjali Nayar]] and [[Hawa Essuman]].<ref name=Silas>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tiff.net/tiff/silas/ |title=Silas|website=www.tiff.net|language=|access-date=6 May 2018}}</ref>

