[[File:BD Bangshi River.jpg|thumb|The river at Aminbazar-Gabtoli, [[Dhaka]]]] [[File:ঢাকার আশুলিয়া বাজারের কাছে তুরাগ নদী.jpg|thumb|The river at [[Ashulia]]]] [[File:Death of Turag River (Amin Bazar, Savar).JPG|thumb|An industrialized and obstructed section of the river]] [[File:Banglar Nau.JPG|thumb|The river at [[Mirpur Model Thana|Mirpur, Dhaka]]]] The '''Turag River''' ({{lang-bn|তুরাগ নদী}} {{IPA-be|t̪uraɡ nɔd̪i|}}) is the upper [[tributary]] of the [[Buriganga River|Buriganga]], a major river in [[Bangladesh]]. The Turag originates from the [[Bangshi River]], the latter an important ''tributary'' of the [[Dhaleshwari River]], flows through [[Gazipur District|Gazipur]] and joins the Buriganga at [[Mirpur Thana|Mirpur]] in [[Dhaka District]]. It is [[navigable]] by boat all year round.
The Turag suffers from [[Land reclamation|infilling]] along its banks, which restricts its flow.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/frontpage/time-declare-turag-dead-1310182 |title=Time to declare Turag dead: River-grabbers appear mightier than govt, judiciary; all steps go in vain |author=Tawfique Ali |date=6 November 2016 |newspaper=The Daily Star}}</ref> It also suffers from acute [[water pollution]]. While attempts have been made to marginally widen the river,<ref name="widen">{{cite news | last = Roy | first = Pinaki | date = 2007-04-21 | url = http://archive.thedailystar.net/2007/04/21/d7042101044.htm | title = Turag gets a new lease of life | newspaper = The Daily Star | access-date = 2007-04-29 }}</ref> the majority of industry has made little effort to follow environmental law<ref name="law">{{cite news | last = Bin Habib | first = Talha | date = 2007-04-29 | url = http://www.theindependent-bd.com/details.php?nid=29540 | title = Pollution sounds the deathknell of Turag | newspaper = The Independent | location = Dhaka | format = PHP | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070928155724/http://www.theindependent-bd.com/details.php?nid=29540 | archive-date = 2007-09-28 | access-date = 2007-04-29 }}</ref> and the water has become visibly discolored.
==History== Earlier this river was called as (Bengali: "Kohor Doriya"), "Kohor river".
==Religious significance==
[[Tablighi Jamaat|Tabligh Jam'at]], a popular [[Islam]]ic movement originating in [[South Asia]], initially took hold in Dhaka in the 1950s as Maulana Abdul Aziz and other leaders set up the regional headquarters at the [[Kakrail Mosque]] near [[Ramna Park]]. An initiative of the movement is an emphasis on the six ''uṣūl'' or "basic principles," two of which include ''ilm'', the pursuit of knowledge, and ''dhikr'' or ''zikr'', a method of prayer involving repetitive invocation of [[hadith]] and [[Qur'an]] passages. To this end, the movement places importance on ''ijtema'' or assembly, where members gather to practice and participate in ''dhikr'', hear religious sermons and discuss their activities.
The largest of these, the [[Bishwa Ijtema]], is situated by the Turag River in Tongi and attracts estimates of between two and four million [[Muslim]]s annually as well as representatives from over sixty countries, making it the second biggest Islamic congregation after the [[Hajj]].<ref name="biswa">{{cite news | author = <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> | date = 2007-02-04 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/6328723.stm | title = Dhaka pilgrimage draws millions | work=BBC News | accessdate = 2007-04-29 }}</ref>
