The '''Tyson Turbine''' is a [[hydropower]] system that extracts power from the flow of water. This design doesn't need a casement, as it is inserted directly into flowing water. It consists of a [[propeller]] mounted below a [[raft]], driving a power system, typically a [[generator (device)|generator]], on top of the raft by belt or gear.<ref>{{cite conference|last=Tuckey|first=A.M. |author2=D.J. Pattereson |author3=and J. Sewnson|title=A Kinetic Energy Tidal Generator in the Northern Territory – Results|conference=23rd International Conference on Industrial Electronics, Control and Instrumentation IECON 97|date=November 1997|pages=937–942}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Anyi|first=M.J. |author2=G. Bhuyana |author3=M.T. Iqbal |author4=J.E. Quaicoe|title=Hydrokinetic energy conversion systems and assessment of horizontal and vertical axis turbines for river and tidal applications: A technology status review|journal=Applied Energy|year=2009|volume=86|pages=1823–1835|doi=10.1016/j.apenergy.2009.02.017}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Anyi|first=Martin|author2=Brian Kirke |title=Evaluation of small axial flow hydrokinetic turbines for remote communities|journal=[[Energy for Sustainable Development]]|year=2010|volume=14|pages=110–116|doi=10.1016/j.esd.2010.02.003}}</ref> The turbine is towed into the middle of a [[river]] or [[stream]], where the flow is the fastest, and tied off to [[shore]]. It requires no local engineering, and can easily be moved to other locations. The Tyson Turbine is a very common way to reuse energy.

